<div id="review_2912213458" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2912213458" />
    <a title="Giorgio" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7311349-giorgio"><img alt="Giorgio" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1325521797p2/7311349.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2912213458?book_show_action=true">Sep 05, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Giorgio" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Giorgio" href="/user/show/7311349-giorgio">Giorgio</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9788807815812" href="/book/show/9667053-il-mondo-incantato">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2912213458" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4781891696570363851">Beautiful excursus through some of the most meaningful fairytales, their symbols and their significance in our growth process. You can look back at your own childhood through this (Freudian) lens, to see what you had to fix and how you (with or against your parents) did it, and maybe find something that you still have to fix today.<br/><br/>Main learnings:<br/>– The classic form of fairy tales was shaped in centuries and sometimes millennia, by storytellers who adjusted to children&apos;s reactions and their own se</span>
  <span id="freeText4781891696570363851" style="display:none">Beautiful excursus through some of the most meaningful fairytales, their symbols and their significance in our growth process. You can look back at your own childhood through this (Freudian) lens, to see what you had to fix and how you (with or against your parents) did it, and maybe find something that you still have to fix today.<br /><br />Main learnings:<br />– The classic form of fairy tales was shaped in centuries and sometimes millennia, by storytellers who adjusted to children's reactions and their own sensitivities. Before washing them to make them more friendly, funny, illustrated, short, modern, reflecting "feminist" values, we should think about what we do not know about them.<br />– Let children pick their stories and tell them repeatedly. Both they and we can learn a lot without even knowing why.<br />– The Ugly Duckling is a terrible story that gives children a figurative inspiration to abandon their own family just because they look different, thinking they may belong to another species altogether.<br />– Disney did not make a bad job in his interpretation: most classical key elements are still there in Cinderella, Snow White, the Sleeping Beauty, the Beauty and the Beast, including the "lost in the wood" phases and the clear terrible punishment of the bad guys.<br />– Those who complain about the princesses passively waiting for their princes have not understood anything of those stories, and they should be told them again, urgently.<br /><br />The Italian translation of the book is quite horrible, but nevertheless, it's another must-read, especially for parents.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4781891696570363851" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


