<div id="review_2135417098" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2135417098" />
    <a title="Brittany Y" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/14271240-brittany-y"><img alt="Brittany Y" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1637184348p2/14271240.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2135417098?book_show_action=true">Mar 29, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Brittany Y" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Brittany Y" href="/user/show/14271240-brittany-y">Brittany Y</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2135417098" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5987313558771966852">I throughly enjoyed the deconstructive nature of this book. It was educational in it&apos;s ability to disassemble popular fairy tales to their foundational values and explain the myths in an easy-to- comprehend way. <br/><br/>I can absolutely see his freudian influence (oral fixation is present in almost all of his analyses) which he was widely criticized for but given the publication date of this book - is that really his fault? Freud provided a basis for psychoanalytic analysis and his theories however wild</span>
  <span id="freeText5987313558771966852" style="display:none">I throughly enjoyed the deconstructive nature of this book. It was educational in it's ability to disassemble popular fairy tales to their foundational values and explain the myths in an easy-to- comprehend way. <br /><br />I can absolutely see his freudian influence (oral fixation is present in almost all of his analyses) which he was widely criticized for but given the publication date of this book - is that really his fault? Freud provided a basis for psychoanalytic analysis and his theories however wild they might have been were widely accepted during that time. My suggestion to the reader is to merely be aware of Bettelheim's influence while reading the book. </span>
  <a data-text-id="5987313558771966852" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


