<div id="review_1524495267" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1524495267" />
    <a title="Peter" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10023481-peter"><img alt="Peter" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1632003602p2/10023481.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1524495267?book_show_action=true">Jan 25, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Peter" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Peter" href="/user/show/10023481-peter">Peter</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/10023481-peter?shelf=myth-and-religion">myth-and-religion</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1524495267" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18333300307977767746">I have two young children, and most of the time I have no idea what is going on in their heads. They struggle, no doubt, with fears, concerns, and disturbing behaviors in others. They may worry about whether they will succeed in the future, and how they can cope in the world. But most of the time they don’t. They just take things as they come. Or so it seems to me. <br/><br/>On the existence of the subconscious, I have no doubt. Through years of observation of myself, I realize that my own actions unconsc</span>
  <span id="freeText18333300307977767746" style="display:none">I have two young children, and most of the time I have no idea what is going on in their heads. They struggle, no doubt, with fears, concerns, and disturbing behaviors in others. They may worry about whether they will succeed in the future, and how they can cope in the world. But most of the time they don’t. They just take things as they come. Or so it seems to me. <br /><br />On the existence of the subconscious, I have no doubt. Through years of observation of myself, I realize that my own actions unconsciously affect my feelings about myself and (or, hence) my feelings and expectations about others, and without conscious effort these feelings can go uncontrolled. And so, surely, children must also wonder about this. And they must wonder about how they will get along in life. They must wonder about who they are, how they should act, and what is the right thing to do?<br /><br />You can answer these questions outright. But sometimes that doesn’t dispel the worry or answer the question. Or you can entertain them, you can take them on a trip in their mind, hint that there might be magic, or simply incredible possibilities, give them a reason to hope that they too, will be an amazing adult. Oh the places you will go! <br /><br />This book points out that you can get the same effect of hope with trolls, witches, glass mountains, talking animals, egotistical kings, evil brothers, dim witted boys, nasty stepmothers and flakey girls. The fantasy and enchantment approach takes the whole band wagon out to a safe distance where it can be observed and laughed at. And it is so entertaining to boot. My boys, surprisingly, loved the fairy tales I started reading to them some time ago. All the challenges, risks, adventures, impossible tasks in order to inherit the kingdom—they eat it up. <br /><br />There is, though, a lot of Freudian analysis in this book. There are oedipal cravings, oral anxieties, oral cravings and oedipal conflicts. There are sibling rivalries, early pubertal conflicts and inter- generational sexual rivalry. At a point quite early on, it gets to be ‘too much already’. For me, that peak of overload was reached with a discussion of Little Red Riding Hood, namely, the assertion that Little Red Riding Hood intentionally ratted out her grandmother’s location to the wolf because the girl was jealous of her grandmother as a sexual rival.<br /><br />Give it a rest!<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="18333300307977767746" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


