        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1483246167" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1419001651463731261">When I first opened this book I thought how I would read about the real meanings of the stories you are told when you are a child when analised. What I found was a book on childrens development through fairy tales and stories, and their meaning to the childs subconscious world.<br/>The further you dive into this book you realize how much of a child still lives in you, and, personally it brings some insight for young people leaving home and experiencing how the first steps away from your parents home </span>
  <span id="freeText1419001651463731261" style="display:none">When I first opened this book I thought how I would read about the real meanings of the stories you are told when you are a child when analised. What I found was a book on childrens development through fairy tales and stories, and their meaning to the childs subconscious world.<br />The further you dive into this book you realize how much of a child still lives in you, and, personally it brings some insight for young people leaving home and experiencing how the first steps away from your parents home feels like and why this feelings live in us.<br />I would never think of this book helping me realize so much of ones struggles, such as my own, the ones we are not really aware of. It highlights the importance of childhood for a better develpoment to a stable adult and how reality is not always the best way to trully understand the real self debates, and ones dictomy over life and choices. <br />It brings to the surface alot of questions you ask yourself through growing up, as a phase you are passing by, and it’s is important to not deny that we experience those questions even if we think we are already grown up adults and we don’t need any of this anymore. It is not about how adult you are, but about the missing links to stability and fulfilment. <br />It is interesintg how we are taught that fantasy and imagination is of most importance when it comes to dealing with life, problems and anxiety, so stories and fairy tales that stimulate that fantasy/imagination of which we are lacking is a big part of life and of future streght and independence.<br />The author gives a clear accent on the child but he talks alot about the parents, and some adult problems that can be reflected on his attitudes towards his children, their education and their emotional life, emphasising the importance of your parents and our relationship with them.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1419001651463731261" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


